I am creating PRs via the Bitbucket API and can create and update them fine:

{code}
#!powershell

$request = [ordered] @{
        title = (&#x27;Automated Deployment to &#x27; + $targetBranch.ToUpper() + &#x27; - &#x27; + (Get-Date -Format yyyy-MM-dd_HH-mm))
        description = $prReason
        destination = @{
            branch = @{
                name = $targetBranch
            }
        }
        source = @{
            branch = @{
                name = $sourceBranch
            }
        }
    }

$newPR = Invoke-RestMethod -Method Post `
                                   -Uri "$bitbucketURL/$repoName/pullrequests" `
                                   -Body ($request | ConvertTo-Json) `
                                   -Headers [~legacy-bitbucket-user] `
                                   -Authentication Basic -Credential $bitbucketCreds
{code}

However when I try to decline PRs using the [decline endpoint|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%257Busername%257D/%257Brepo_slug%257D/pullrequests/%257Bpull_request_id%257D/decline]:

{code}
#!powershell

$declinedPR = Invoke-RestMethod -Method Put `
                                        -Uri "$bitbucketURL/$repoName/pullrequests/$($newPR.id)/decline" `
                                        -Body  ($request | ConvertTo-Json) `
                                        -Headers [~legacy-bitbucket-user] `
                                        -Authentication Basic -Credential $bitbucketCreds


{code}

I get the following HTTP 403 response:

{code}
Invoke-RestMethod : This endpoint does not support token-based authentication
+         $declinedPR = Invoke-RestMethod -Method Put `
+                       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
+ CategoryInfo          : InvalidOperation: (Method: PUT, Re...ication/json
}:HttpRequestMessage) [Invoke-RestMethod], HttpResponseException
+ FullyQualifiedErrorId : WebCmdletWebResponseException,Microsoft.PowerShell.Commands.InvokeRestMethodCommand
{code}

Currently seems like Pipelines unnecessary cache(?) earlier fetched GitHub fork which results in failed build - i.e.:

{code}
#!js
...
dependencies: {
		"redux-query": "vizum/redux-query",
}
...

{code}

Using Yarn with same commands as in Pipelines on my local CLI works as intended - latest version of code has been pulled from GitHub and project has been build.

I&#x27;ve tried clearing caches by pressing Pipelines dedicated button and by removing "node_modules" by hand in Pipelines script, but without success.

Repo with issue:\\
https://bitbucket.org/vizum/vizum-info-web/addon/pipelines/home

On the attached screenshot you can see that package version is mismatched, but even without bumping it Yarn should download the master branch HEAD (latest commit).

On a new repository&#x27;s source page, the "Get your local Git repository on Bitbucket" sections shows the following steps:

Step 1: Switch to your repository&#x27;s directory

{code}
cd /path/to/your/repo
{code}

Step 2: Connect your existing repository to Bitbucket

{code}
git remote set-url origin git@bitbucket.org:leonstestteam/test-repo-2.git
git push -u origin master

{code}

These steps make sense when you are adding an existing repository with an existing origin but it should explain that the correct line for an existing repository without an existing origin should be presented as git remote add origin git@bitbucket.org:renesmadsen/eform2018.git and then git push -u origin master

Right now when merging PR into the repository there is one predefined look of commit message that looks like:

{{one line: Merged in something (pull request #number)}}

{{list of: commit messages}}

{{list of: approvals}}

This breaks things like https://github.com/commitizen/cz-cli that parses git messages and expect them in a specific format.

It would be great if at least default template could be modified that {{Merged}} line can be placed after list of commit messages.

It would be even better if there would be full template setting in repository when those predefined sections could be freeely moved.

Thank you

Hi,

I am not sure if this belongs here but, there was a change on {{gcloud}} and now you must set up your access to Google&#x27;s gcr.io using the following command:

{code}
#!sh

gcloud auth configure-docker
{code}

Unfortunately, this command can eventually freeze and if you don&#x27;t set up a timeout, you&#x27;ll end up burning 120 minutes of your pipelines plan on each invocation (this took away $200 last month from me).

Any ideas what is going on?

In settings: Merge strategy = &#x27;Fast forward&#x27;

Clicking Merge in PR results in popup with textarea to enter commit message and it defaults to same message as for Merge strategy.

Changing strategy sets proper behaviour - no textarea for fast-forward (we expect same commit message)

When creating a new repository, the message shown is this: !603210439-Screen%20Shot%202018-06-21%20at%2013.49.38.png|thumbnail!

However this is not correct, as it suggests the usage of

{code}
#!git

git remote set-url
{code}

But it should be suggesting:

{code}
#!git

git remote add
{code}

This issue cannot be reproduced on my desktop (Debian GNU/Linux 9.4 (stretch)/Docker 18.03.1-ce).

When running my Makefile on pipeline this command

{code}
#!bash

docker build -t quay.io/greenpass/mytaggy-batch-billing:unstable-982f2ab -f MyTaggy.Batch.Billing/Dockerfile MyTaggy.Batch.Billing/bin/Release/netcoreapp2.1/publish/
{code}

the pipeline returns the following error:

{code}
#!bash

unable to prepare context: the Dockerfile (/opt/atlassian/pipelines/agent/build/MyTaggy.Batch.Billing/Dockerfile) must be within the build context
make: *** [mytaggy-batch-billing] Error 1
Makefile:14: recipe for target &#x27;mytaggy-batch-billing&#x27; failed
{code}

Is there any way to update the docker service version (I am unable to run a custom docker service since --privileged is disabled) to solve this issue? I really don&#x27;t want to copy the Dockerfile to the build context folder before this command.

Regards,

When I use the following url:

{code}
#!python

https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories?role=member&sort=updated_on
{code}

and then check the &#x27;next&#x27; key in the response, i see an url like this:

{code}
#!python

https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories?sort=updated_on&after=2016-08-30T12%3A59%3A02.440738%2B00%3A00&role=member
{code}

This is fine, it will loop me back to the beginning of times

However, if i use the url:

{code}
#!python

https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories?role=member&sort=-updated_on
{code}

and then check the next field I would expect the response to contain a search for &#x27;before&#x27; to be able to loop to beginning of times. Instead, the next field contains this url:

{code}
#!python

https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories?sort=-updated_on&after=2017-11-10T13%3A40%3A17.624877%2B00%3A00&role=member
{code}

This way i can only request one page, unless i build the next url myself.
